// C2: Acting Components
instance PermanentMagnetSynchronousMotor : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Permanent magnet synchronous motor used for motion control in the MABI MAX 100 robot's first axis, interfaced with Siemens SINUMERIK 840D sl controller for separate axis control with configurable position/speed/acceleration inputs."
]

instance AxisController : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Siemens SINUMERIK 840D sl controller enabling programmable motion profiles with safety constraints including maximum working range [-90°, 90°] and maximum speed |q_dot_max| = 75°/s, with hardware-level positional limits and software monitoring."
]

// C3: Physical Sensing Components
instance MotorPositionEncoder : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "High-resolution position encoder mounted directly on the motor shaft providing real-time positional feedback for backlash compensation and low-rigidity mitigation in the mechanical system."
    DTDFVocab:producedData MotorPositionData
]

instance OutputShaftEncoder : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Secondary high-resolution position encoder positioned behind the gearbox providing output shaft angle measurements for positional accuracy verification and redundancy with motor encoder readings."
    DTDFVocab:producedData OutputShaftData
]

instance MotorCurrentSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Current sensor measuring input current traces for motor torque estimation and dynamic behavior analysis of the first axis."
    DTDFVocab:producedData MotorCurrentData
]

// C4: Physical-to-Virtual Interaction
instance MotorPositionData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom MotorPositionEncoder
]

instance OutputShaftData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom OutputShaftEncoder
]

instance MotorCurrentData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom MotorCurrentSensor
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance SysMLInternalBlockDiagram : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "SysML Internal Block Diagram representing the MABI MAX 100 robot's component-connector architecture including joints, actuators, and sensors as interconnected entities for functional/logical architecture modeling."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SysMLToolchain
]

instance FrictionSimulationModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Executable friction model of the first axis implemented in MathWorks MATLAB Simulink for physics-based validation of dynamic behaviors and operational constraints."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SimulinkToolchain
]

instance KinematicBehaviorModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Simulink-based executable model capturing the robot's kinematic and dynamic states for real-time behavioral analysis and validation against SysML architecture."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SimulinkToolchain
]

instance ProcessedSensorData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Aggregated and abstracted sensor data traces (position, current, angle measurements) filtered, normalized, and structured for Digital Twin analysis and simulation input."
    DTDFVocab:fromData MotorPositionData, OutputShaftData, MotorCurrentData
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataProcessingPipeline, SimulinkToolchain
]

instance DigitalShadowData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Contextual data traces representing the physical system's state for manufacturing process monitoring, derived from one-way data flows per Digital Shadow Reference Model."
    DTDFVocab:fromData ProcessedSensorData
    DTDFVocab:inputTo VisualizationDashboard, BehavioralAnalysisService
]

// C11: Enablers
instance SysMLToolchain : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "SysML-based modeling environment enabling Internal Block Diagrams for architectural decomposition of the MABI MAX 100 robot's component-connector structure."
    DTDFVocab:enables ArchitectureModelingService
]

instance SimulinkToolchain : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "MathWorks MATLAB Simulink environment for executable simulation models of friction dynamics and kinematic behavior, integrated with SysML architecture for behavioral validation."
    DTDFVocab:enables BehavioralAnalysisService, SimulationValidationService
]

instance DataProcessingPipeline : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Automated data processing pipeline implementing filtering, normalization, and abstraction of raw sensor data for Digital Twin consumption via MQTT protocol."
    DTDFVocab:enables DataAggregationService
]

instance VisualizationDashboard : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Dashboard interface for real-time visualization of system data, simulation results, and behavioral analysis outputs for stakeholder interaction."
    DTDFVocab:enables MonitoringService, DecisionSupportService
]

// C6: Services
instance ArchitectureModelingService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service providing SysML-based architectural modeling of the MABI MAX 100 robot's component-connector structure for functional/logical decomposition."
    DTDFVocab:provides ArchitectureInsight
]

instance DataAggregationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service aggregating and abstracting raw sensor data into structured formats for Digital Twin use via one-way data flows."
    DTDFVocab:provides DataAbstractionInsight
]

instance BehavioralAnalysisService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service performing simulation-driven behavioral modeling (friction dynamics, kinematics) to support predictive maintenance and performance optimization."
    DTDFVocab:provides FrictionAnalysisInsight, KinematicInsight
]

instance MonitoringService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service providing continuous real-time data aggregation and abstraction of the physical system's state for joint friction identification and operational monitoring."
    DTDFVocab:provides OperationalStateInsight
]

instance SimulationValidationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service validating simulation models against real-time sensor data to ensure behavioral accuracy and operational constraint compliance."
    DTDFVocab:provides ModelValidationInsight
]

instance DecisionSupportService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service providing contextual data-driven insights for engineering stakeholders, operators, and maintenance personnel."
    DTDFVocab:provides MaintenanceRecommendationAction
]

// C17: Insights/Actions
instance ArchitectureInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Insight derived from SysML Internal Block Diagrams showing the robot's component-connector architecture and modular design."
]

instance DataAbstractionInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Insight representing the structured abstraction of raw sensor data into meaningful Digital Twin data formats."
]

instance FrictionAnalysisInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Insight from friction simulation models identifying dynamic behaviors and operational constraints in the first axis."
]

instance KinematicInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Insight into the robot's kinematic states derived from executable simulation models for performance analysis."
]

instance OperationalStateInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Real-time insight into the physical system's operational state including joint positions, motor currents, and dynamic behaviors."
]

instance ModelValidationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Insight validating the accuracy of simulation models against real-time sensor data for behavioral consistency."
]

instance MaintenanceRecommendationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Actionable recommendation for predictive maintenance based on behavioral analysis and operational data trends."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic false
]

// C1: Environment
instance ManufacturingEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:desc "Operational environment for the MABI MAX 100 robot in precision manufacturing tasks with safety constraints including maximum working range [-90°, 90°] and speed limits."
    base:contains PermanentMagnetSynchronousMotor, AxisController, MotorPositionEncoder, OutputShaftEncoder, MotorCurrentSensor
]

// C5: Components
instance RobotFirstAxis : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "First axis of the MABI MAX 100 serial robot incorporating articulated joints with explicit friction modeling for dynamic behavior analysis."
    base:isContainedIn ManufacturingEnvironment
]

instance GearboxAssembly : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Mechanical gearbox assembly within the first axis providing speed reduction and torque multiplication with integrated secondary encoder for positional accuracy."
    base:isContainedIn RobotFirstAxis
]

instance ControllerInterface : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Interface between the robot's actuation system and Siemens SINUMERIK 840D sl controller enabling programmable motion profiles and safety constraint enforcement."
    base:isContainedIn RobotFirstAxis
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system operates with real-time, data-driven synchronization between the physical robot axis and its digital representation, leveraging executable simulation models implemented in **MathWorks MATLAB Simulink** for behavioral modeling. Sensor data is streamed via **MQTT**, enabling low-latency, continuous updates between the physical system and the digital shadow. The system explicitly emphasizes real-time processing to ensure temporal alignment, though explicit synchronization frequencies (e.g., Hz or ms intervals) are not detailed in the provided documents. Latency requirements are implicitly implied by the use of live-data streaming and the integration of time-series sensor data for friction modeling, ensuring sub-second responsiveness for operational decision-making."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system’s orchestration and coordination are structured around MBSE frameworks that integrate heterogeneous modeling tools and notations. Key architecture patterns include the use of ADLs (e.g., AADL, ACME) for component & connector modeling, combined with behavioral descriptions via SysML state machines or MontiArc Automaton. Resource management is implied through the modular decomposition of system models, where each layer (e.g., logical, physical) operates as a semi-autonomous entity. System-wide coordination is achieved via shared interfaces and connectors defined in ADLs, enabling data and control flow synchronization across twin instances. The integration of simulation tools (e.g., Simulink) and general-purpose languages (e.g., C++, Java) further supports cross-layer coordination, though explicit orchestration frameworks (e.g., microservices, event-driven architectures) are not mentioned."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "
The lifecycle of a Digital Twin (DT) system is structured through **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies, which decompose system modeling into distinct abstraction layers: **requirements, functional architecture, logical architecture, and product/technical layers**. Transition management between these stages is facilitated by **architecture description languages (ADLs)** such as **ACME, AADL, MontiArc, or SysML Internal Block Diagrams (IBDs)**, which define components, interfaces, connectors, and composition rules. Behavior modeling is further refined using **state machines (SysML v1.7) or MontiArc Automata**, often integrated with simulation tools like **MathWorks Simulink** or general-purpose languages (C++, Java). Lifecycle governance involves **heterogeneous stakeholder integration** and **multi-tool interoperability**, addressing complexity through methodologies like **RFLP (Requirements, Functions, Logics, Physics), OOSEM, SPES, or SMArDT**. Transition between stages is governed by **formalized abstraction hierarchies**, ensuring traceability and consistency across modeling artifacts. No explicit lifecycle governance frameworks (e.g., ISO/IEC 42010) are referenced in the document, but the reliance on **MBSE standards** implies compliance with **systems engineering best practices** for lifecycle management.
"
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system prioritizes **model fidelity** by analyzing the **deviation between simulated and measured data** to identify sources of inaccuracy, including **joint friction** and **low rigidity**. Validation is conducted through **comparative analysis** of simulated outputs against real-world measurements, though no explicit **quantification of uncertainty** or **error correction mechanisms** are described. **Quality assurance** processes are implied through the alignment of models with physical behavior, though no formalized thresholds, closed-loop testing, or calibration procedures (e.g., dual-encoder calibration) are mentioned in the documents."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The technical network infrastructure for this Digital Twin system is not explicitly detailed in the provided documents. However, the **digital shadow reference model** implies reliance on **MQTT** for sensor data communication, though no further specifics (e.g., network topology, bandwidth, latency, or security protocols like TLS) are mentioned. The system may involve **heterogeneous stakeholders and perspectives** requiring integration, but no explicit protocols (e.g., OPC UA, DDS) or redundancy mechanisms are referenced. The document does not provide details on cloud-edge-on-premise architectures or communication protocols beyond the one-way flow described for digital shadows."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system adheres to **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE) standards**, including **SysML (OMG standard)** for architecture modeling and **architecture description languages (ADLs)** like **AADL (SAE AS5506)** and **MontiArc** for component-based design. Interoperability is addressed through **heterogeneous tool integration** (e.g., SysML + Simulink) and **multi-perspective modeling** (requirements, functional, logical, physical layers). No explicit compliance with **industry-specific DT standards** (e.g., ISO/IEC 23247, IEC 62424) or **certification frameworks** is mentioned. The document references **Kritzinger et al.’s digital shadow model** (UML class diagram) but does not extend to **formal DT standardization** (e.g., ontologies, semantic interoperability). **Interoperability standards** are implied via **ADL and MBSE tool compatibility**, but no specific protocols (e.g., OPC UA, DDS) or data exchange formats (e.g., JSON-LD, RDF) are cited.
"
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system described in the provided documents incorporates **cybersecurity protocols** and **safety mechanisms** primarily through the **Asset Administration Shell (AAS)** framework and **RAMI 4.0** architecture. Specifically, the **safety cell of the robotic system (e.g., MABI robotic arm)** restricts the maximum working range to **2.25 meters** (as per [44]), ensuring physical safety by confining operational zones. While the documents do not explicitly detail **role-based access control (RBAC)** or **ISO 13849 compliance**, the **AAS** (as referenced in [46], [47], and [50]) serves as a standardized structure for **secure data exchange** within the **Industrie 4.0 automation pyramid**, enabling **threat mitigation** through **semantic interoperability** and **data traceability**.

For **data communication**, the system leverages **MQTT (Message Queuing Telemetry Transport)**—implemented via **Mosquitto** ([52])—to stream **real-time sensor data** from the physical asset to its digital counterpart. This protocol ensures **low-latency, reliable transmission** of telemetry, which is critical for **fail-safe mechanisms** in industrial automation. However, no explicit mention of **encryption standards (e.g., TLS), authentication systems (e.g., OAuth), or risk assessment methodologies** (e.g., ISO/IEC 27001) is provided in the documents.

The **functional mockup interface (FMI)** ([51]) further supports **simulation-based safety validation**, enabling **model-in-the-loop (MIL) and hardware-in-the-loop (HIL) testing** to verify system behavior under **extreme or failure conditions**. While these measures address **safety-critical considerations**, the documents do not elaborate on **privacy-preserving techniques (e.g., differential privacy) or compliance with GDPR/CCPA** for data governance."
]